28:53.991 --> 29:00.859
believe, if I'm not badly mistaken, and I don't 
think I am, Dr. Perry at Fredericksburg has that in

29:01.396 --> 29:06.508
that old two-story house. And he bought it from 
Oriole. And Uncle Jesse, it was his, given to Aunt

29:09.656 --> 29:17.835
Kate. Aunt Kate was Oriole's mother, and so I'm 
sure that that's where that bed is. But anyway, I

29:24.451 --> 29:25.954
learned to count. I would get up, but never could I. 
I could get up to five, and I'd forget what six was

29:26.415 --> 29:32.987
every time. So one day he told me, he said, six, 
remember you're sick. You're a sick little girl

29:39.888 --> 29:41.951
when you get there. You're going to be sick because 
I'm going to pat you if you don't get over it. Well, I

29:45.437 --> 29:47.300
got there, and I said, I'm sick. And he said, no, 
you're six. All right, that's how I learned six.

29:54.491 --> 29:58.177
And so then we got on, and I could count to 10. And 
then from 10, he'd say, 10 and one more. And he'd

30:03.005 --> 30:04.767
hold up two fingers. And then I'd have to count the 
next bedpost. And that was the way it rings around

30:07.985 --> 30:10.808
it. Well, this bedpost had 10 on it. And then it'd be 
10 and one would be 11. And I learned how to write

30:17.896 --> 30:24.844
those just because he'd say, what's the next one 
now? It was a two, wasn't it? Well, you've got the 10

30:26.125 --> 30:27.707
over here. You've got to put that one down. And then 
put your two down. And you've got your 10 over here,

30:32.639 --> 30:36.543
and you're just adding on to it. Now, you'll 
remember that, he'd say. You've already got your

30:39.446 --> 30:40.667
10. You're just adding one more to it, or you're 
adding two more to it. It's 10 and 2. 10 and 3. Well,

30:46.874 --> 30:47.995
that's 13. And that's how I was taught to count the 
bedpost circles. 10 and 3. And they say today you

30:55.603 --> 31:00.768
have modern math. Uh-uh. It's been here always.

