38:49.826 --> 38:51.049
give it to Debbie. I didn't give her the pair. I just 
had the one when I gave it to the partner. I would say

38:55.698 --> 38:57.721
another question here. You learned how to survive 
in a man's world as well as in a woman's world. I sure

39:03.698 --> 39:04.560
did. You had no choice. Your mother, of course, 
would have been in the same tradition because

39:05.562 --> 39:14.240
pioneer women had no choice but to survive in an 
equal world with their men. That was another thing

39:16.245 --> 39:18.730
Uncle Taxi taught me to do. What was this? It was 
every evening we'd go down this trail, we had

39:19.712 --> 39:23.901
shoemake. that grew out around. And the life of a 
shoemake tree is quite short. And we'd go over and

39:30.220 --> 39:37.210
we'd break off just so much to start our fire with 
the next morning. And from a little child, I have

39:37.931 --> 39:46.604
been taking in kindling and things to start a fire 
with in the morning. And let me tell you something.

39:49.267 --> 39:52.412
The old folks didn't let their fire die out. 
Uh-huh. We didn't have matches. So you kept that

39:55.740 --> 39:58.082
fire going all the time. You kept that fire going 
all the time. And you'd bank it in the summertime.

40:02.867 --> 40:09.653
You'd bank it at night, cover it up with ashes so 
you'd have a coal to start with the next morning.

40:09.673 --> 40:11.855
Because your flame is what kept you cooking. 
That's right. Laundry and all these things.

40:15.018 --> 40:15.778
Everything. That's right. And he was the very one 
that taught me how to break it off, where to get it.

40:26.382 --> 40:29.986
And we didn't have cedar in those days.

40:32.549 --> 40:35.633
We had shoemake to start our fire with. And he would 
use the shoemake and then dry leaves. And I'd bring

40:43.181 --> 40:49.288
in, I'd find dry leaves or something and I'd bring 
it in to my mother and put it down. And a corn cob. But

40:51.867 --> 40:55.914
listen, we didn't use but one or two corn cobs at a 
time. Why is that?

41:00.141 --> 41:08.155
Well, we would use them the year round to start 
fires with if our fire went out. And coal oil was

41:08.793 --> 41:11.879
what we used to put in the land. Now then, this fuzz 
on the outside of a corn cob would ignite and catch

41:11.899 --> 41:20.657
quick. So you would take about a teaspoon full of 
coal oil and string it up and down this corn cob. and

41:27.912 --> 41:33.398
then put it in there to start your fire with, and it 
would burn. That would catch, and it would really

41:33.459 --> 41:39.606
catch on fire and burn, and it would dry out and burn 
real good. And you saved your corn top, so you'd be

41:40.267 --> 41:46.354
sure to have one all year round. I see. Very good. 
Green corn cobs don't burn. No, they have to be your

41:52.071 --> 41:53.874
dry corn cobs. You bet. They sure do. And you know, 
something else Uncle Jesse taught me. We had to

41:59.265 --> 42:03.734
shell our own corn to go to market to take our meal. 
And I didn't know what the nubbit meant. But he

42:08.750 --> 42:12.438
would say, now I'll shuck it, sister. You take all 
of the bad ones off of the end. All the bad ones off

42:16.086 --> 42:19.634
down here at the butt. Now there's a tussle end and 
the butt end. Right. All right. The ones at the butt

42:24.024 --> 42:27.191
end are usually hard and slick. Yeah. Don't ever 
put that in your meal because it doesn't make good

42:28.375 --> 42:35.022
cornmeal and it doesn't rise good. So you had to 
take all of that off. Well, that was put in a bucket.

42:40.047 --> 42:46.995
All of this up here that was around the edge might be 
worm-eaten or it was never good. You'd shell all of

42:47.375 --> 42:51.219
that off until it was real good and you'd put that in 
a bucket. That's what you fed your chickens. Oh, so

42:54.093 --> 42:55.817
that was nubbing? Is that what you called it? Yes. 
Nubbing the corn? Nubbing the corn, and you fed it

42:57.882 --> 43:01.431
to the chickens. Very good. Sure. Makes sense. 
Now, I'm telling you. Now, those are things that

43:05.862 --> 43:08.127
are very. Those are things that I learned when I 
was. Are you the old? Yeah, under the age of five.

43:14.121 --> 43:15.763
Yes, under the age of five. Your early upbringing 
was concentrated for your survival. That was

43:19.608 --> 43:21.330
right. Which is something that people don't 
realize about Blanco County and Texas being

43:21.430 --> 43:29.320
isolated as it was at that particular time. I want 
to tell you one thing. You were taught, like when

43:31.803 --> 43:37.330
your mother built a fire around the wash pot, you'd 
like to see, she'd take a shovel full of ashes and

43:37.883 --> 43:49.020
throw it up to see which way the wind was. Oh, 
really? That's right, to be sure that she got the

43:50.823 --> 43:53.687
right wind. And that's where you'd build your 
fire, where the wind would blow the fire under the

43:54.469 --> 43:59.617
wash pot. Then you'd put something, if you 
happened to be fortunate enough, that you had a old

44:06.115 --> 44:11.815
piece of tin, which is scarce as hen's teeth. But if 
you had anything that you could hold the heat,

44:11.955 --> 44:18.117
you'd put it around that pot and hold the heat. And 
it would be my job to carry it, go hunt little sticks

44:18.772 --> 44:23.177
and little things. But I didn't go put them in the 
fire. That was a no-no. I piled them down here. My

44:28.083 --> 44:29.105
mother did that. Because there's an art to 
building a fire. There's an art to building a fire.

44:33.650 --> 44:36.714
And we didn't have a whole lot of wood that we could 
go get. Only a way out in the pasture. And our daddy

44:39.097 --> 44:41.560
had to haul it in the wagon. And we took very special 
pains in using it. How much we used and what we used.

44:48.048 --> 44:48.188
Mm-hmm. Sure. To conserve our wood. We don't do 
that today. So most of this early, early childhood

44:55.057 --> 44:59.723
was spent in Stonewall, isn't that right? Yes, 
that's right. That's right there on the river. On

45:04.809 --> 45:06.691
the Perlin Allis River. Where the present-day 
ranch is now. Well, that's up the way. We call that

45:12.538 --> 45:15.222
the big house. Uncle Clarence lived in that. 
Right, okay. And now when they say the Bailey

45:17.845 --> 45:20.368
Lane... When they go by the bus and say the Bailey 
Link. That house that's sitting over there is

45:23.253 --> 45:29.282
exactly like the house that I lived in. And it's 
Cousin Oriole's. My house burned down. But the one

45:33.128 --> 45:37.676
that I was brought up in burned down. But you can see 
it from the boyhood home. I mean the birthplace.

45:42.343 --> 45:44.787
You can see the... windmill and the trees around 
it. That's one thing about the people in the hill

45:48.655 --> 45:51.880
country. They built their houses where there was 
trees that would keep it cool. And they didn't

45:57.148 --> 46:01.654
build it out in the broad open spaces. They had 
trees in their yard.

